Westmoreland Coal: Diamond In The Rough - Westmoreland Coal Co (NASDAQ:WLB) | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»Westmoreland Coal: Diamond In The RoughAug.24.15 | About: Westmoreland Coal (WLB) John Zhang Deep Value, long/short equity, contrarianMarketplaceActionable InsightsSummaryWLB's long-term, cost protected contracts ensure profitability in the long run.The company's mine mouth operations enable cost and time efficiency.WLB is largely shielded from the impact of cheap natural gas.Temporarily depressed earnings figures mask its stronger fundamentals.The market's misunderstanding of WLB's fundamentals leave room for tremendous upside.Westmoreland Coal Company (NASDAQ:WLB) is a coal mining and transportation operator focusing on the niche market in the US and Canada. Like others in the coal industry, WLB's share price has been hit severely due to the downturn in energy prices and the threat from natural gas.


Source: YCharts
However, WLB possesses key advantages that puts it far ahead of other competitors and ensures that it remains profitable for years to come. Furthermore, the market has largely misinterpreted its true financial situation, leading to a very depressed share price. These competitive advantages and current market perception will allow the stock price to outperform peers and the overall market significantly in the years to come.
Long-Term Cost Protected Contracts
Substantially all of WLB's coal is sold under long-term, cost-protected contracts. This means coal sales prices will adjust according to the actual costs associated with mining, including fixed costs. The average remaining length on these contracts as of 2015 was an astounding 11 years, thus indicating that its clients are committed to being in the coal business for decades to come. Moreover, the cost-protection provisions in its supply contracts ensure that coal delivered is priced based on its production costs plus a premium.

Our long-term coal contracts are "cost protected" in that they typically contain either full pass-through of our costs or price escalation and adjustment provisions, pursuant to which the price for our coal may be periodically revised in line with broad economic indicators such as the consumer price index, ...
(Source: WLB 10-K)


This contract structure essentially guarantees profitability for WLB even as coal prices fall. It ensures that WLB will never have to sell coal at a price below its marginal cost of production and accounts fully for the increase in cost of production over time.
Furthermore, the long length of these contracts ensures stable sales volumes. Hence, these contracts reduce both price and volume risks substantially. Compared to other producers that sell under conventional contracts for which sales price adjusts according to the spot or forward price, WLB is largely insulated from the tumult in the coal spot market today as it has price and volume visibility for the next 11 years. This is a crucial factor that explains why it will likely survive the current downturn and prosper thereafter.
Overall, 90% of WLB's coal sales are long-term cost plus/cost indexed contracts, with 49% of these contracts including fixed-cost reimbursements if the customer elects to reduce tonnage delivered. This puts the company in a strong position regardless of how low coal prices stay low.
Below is a summary of its US Operations, with the specifics on contract terms for each mine.


Source: 10-K and Other Filings
As seen, all of Westmoreland's US operations have contracts on a "cost-plus" basis, thus ensuring a floor for coal prices. Moreover, some contracts even have provisions for a minimum return on capital, CapEx and Reclamation cost pass-through, which benefits WLB substantially.
However, profitability is affected by lower commodities prices as supply contracts have clauses that would adjust prices according to indices linked to items such as diesel and gasoline. Hence, while they are largely insulated from coal price declines, WLB's margins did decrease during this period due to the overall fall in commodities indices.

We tried to obtain filings with the Public Utilities Commissions of the different states that Westmoreland operates in to get a clearer look at the terms of its contracts. However, these dockets are filed confidentially and not made available to the public. We did manage to find an interesting case where the Public Regulatory Commission for the state of New Mexico accidentally released a contract between PNM utilities and Westmoreland Coal to a local newspaper, which caused a legal uproar subsequently.


Assuming this contract is representative of the structure of the typical contract Westmoreland enters into, we see clearly that the way that cost-indexing is achieved is through weighting several key costs of production and using them to form an index for quarterly price adjustments. This mechanism ensures prices escalate more than or equivalent to costs over time, as long as the composition of costs does not change drastically and management does not grow complacent in managing costs.
The flip side to Westmoreland's contracting strategy is that its upside is limited if and when coal prices recover as the contract prices largely do not adjust according to the spot market. Hence, WLB would benefit far less than other coal producers in a coal bull market. However, WLB has some exposure to the international market due to its acquisition of Canadian assets from Sherritt International (OTCPK:SHERF), which would become more profitable should coal prices surge.


Source: WLB 10-K, Sherritt International Annual Report, WLB Investor Presentation
A key rationale cited by management for purchasing the Canadian assets was the "long-term cost-protected" contracts that the mines have, which are almost a mirror to WLB's US operations. In addition, the Coal Valley mine offers potential upside when the coal industry recovers as its exports are priced on a spot/forward basis. The mine also has strategic access to ports and rail lines which reduce transport costs and the risk of disruption.
Mine-Mouth Operations
A large majority of WLB's mines are located in close proximity to the power plants that they supply, so close in fact, most of their coal is transported via conveyer belts directly into the coal-fired generators. Five out of six of WLB's mines in Canada are mine-mouth operations where mines are directly adjacent to the power plant, and almost all US mines are able to deliver coal via conveyer belts or trucks to the generators. This is an incredible advantage that substantially decreases transportation costs and gives the company a unique edge over regional competitors.
This also ensures supply is not exposed to the risk of rail disruption or poor weather, which tends to impact financial results significantly during harsh winter conditions.
Unaffected By Cheap Natural Gas
Over the past few years, cheaper natural gas and the retirement of older coal plants have resulted in natural gas comprising a larger percentage in the fuel mix for electricity generation. Concurrently, coal's share has declined.
However, due to the decade-long contracts that WLB has with its customers, along with the fact that the mine-mouth operations enable fast and cost-efficient transportation, WLB's business is unaffected as it has already locked in the coal demand for years to come. Moreover, a portion of Westmoreland's income is derived from leasing out coal properties and collecting royalties on their sales. These are also multi-year leases with profitable terms and will not be terminated anytime soon. Hence, there is little risk to this income stream.

Also, given that new gas power plants would require large capital investments amounting to a few hundred million or over a billion, and new infrastructure such as gas pipelines would need to be built, any shift away from coal to natural gas will take a very long time for WLB's clients.
Another point to note is that even at these natural gas prices, WLB is still delivering coal to its customers at far below the natural-gas equivalent. This is partially due to the cost advantage of having mine-mouth operations and the existing transportation infrastructure, as well as efficient operations.


Source: WLB Investor Presentation
Despite natural gas languishing at multi-year lows, WLB still delivers coal at a lower rate. This illustrates the sustainability of its business.
Disastrous Numbers Mask Stronger Fundamentals

Note: Revenues are aligned to the axis on the right.
As seen above, WLB's cash flows were healthy until they started declining drastically after 2013. At face value, net-income appears to have taken a massive dive as well. However, on closer inspection, we discovered several extraordinary, non-recurring items that have made results appear far worse than they actually are.
1) WLB recorded a loss on debt extinguishment of $49.1M in 2014. It repurchased 10.75% Senior Notes and refinanced part of the debt at a lower rate by issuing 8.75% Senior Notes. Hence, managed to decrease its leverage albeit taking a large one-time charge. Although WLB paid a cash premium to redeem its debt, it serves the company better in the long-run to reduce leverage during tough industry environments. Moreover, the $49.1M was a non-cash charge, and did not affect operating cash flows.

2) The company recorded a derivative loss of $31.1M due to changes in its power-purchase contracts at the ROVA power plants. Essentially, WLB purchases power for the power plants it owns at a fixed price. As energy prices capitulated in 2014, the company had to mark-to-market the loss on the contract as GAAP classifies it as a financial instrument. Hence, WLB would record positive gains when energy prices rebound. In essence, although the charge appears large, it is relatively inconsequential to its operations.
3) WLB incurred $26.8M in acquisition and transition costs due to its purchase of Canadian coal mines and other assets, which it has since spun off into a separate MLP (NYSE:WMLP) in which it owns a 79% stake. These costs are not expected to persist, and were expected as part of the acquisition.
4) WLB incurred a $15M restructuring charge as it reorganized its Canadian assets after acquiring them in 2014. A portion of this cash was also used to restructure WMLP's debt. These are not expected to reoccur.
If we exclude these one-time items, results for 2014 appear significantly better: net income would improve from ($173M) to ($51M). OCF and FCF would also improve substantially from $50.4M to $92.1M, and from $0 to $47.1M respectively. With a current market capitalization of $221M, WLB would have generated a FCF yield of over 21% if we excluded one-time cash expenses. Given this ridiculously high free cash flow yield excluding one-time charges, WLB should be trading far higher than the currently P/S of 0.15.
Hence, we believe once the acquisition is fully integrated and the one-time charges cease, the market will discover WLB's true earnings power, leading to a substantial rally in share price.
Strong Business Model, But Problematic Balance Sheet
We have shown that WLB has a solid, sustainable business model that offers unique advantages compared to other regional competitors. However, its low valuation stems from certain concerns with the balance sheet, which we will now address.

From a glance at the balance sheet, the lay investor would conclude WLB has a serious debt and liabilities problem. We will show the next part of our research that the problem lies not in the size of the liabilities, but the misinterpretation that the size of long-term liabilities reflect the degree of negative impact to the company's financials. In reality, when we break down the cash-flow impact of these liabilities, they are clearly manageable.
WLB has a negative book value mainly due to its long-term debt, asset retirement obligations and pension liabilities. The market seems to have priced in a large probability of default risk due to these three items, but a more in-depth look would suggest that WLB is at little risk of default.
Breaking Down Large Liabilities
The sheer amount of liabilities on WLB's balance sheet is a major reason for its rock-bottom valuation: it trades at a P/S of 0.16, which is cheap even by coal industry standards. However, WLB has a negative book value, largely due to the $990M in long-term debt, $401M in asset retirement obligations and $293M in post-retirement benefits on its balance sheet. We shall split our analysis on these three items.
1) Long-Term Debt

Source: SEC Filings
Interest coverage ratios for the past few years paints a bleak picture. However, when analyzing the debt profile of WLB in this harsh environment, our key criteria is survivability. We note that EBITDA and EBIT interest coverage dropped dramatically in 2014 due to the one-time charges mentioned earlier. If we exclude these non-recurring items, EBITDA coverage would be at 1.52, clearly indicating that WLB is able to meet interest payments without further issuance of debt or equity.


Future interest expense are expected to stay fairly stable assuming WLB does not take on additional debt to fund purchases. The company's CEO has stated in previous conference calls that he intends to deleverage going forward, and to fund purchases through the drop-down from WMLP instead of having the parent company take on further debt. Hence, we can expect lower overall leverage going forward.
Overall, EBITDA is sufficient to fund long-term interest payments for the foreseeable future. Although the sheer size ($990M) of WLB's long-term debt seems risky, the reality is that interest expenses are fairly sustainable and does not put the company at a high risk of default.
2) Asset Retirement Obligations (ARO)
This liability stems from the need to reclaim the land that the coal mine sits on after mines are depleted. Again, whilst the $401M figure is huge, it does not accurately reflect the cash flows required to manage this liability.
For 2015, WLB will incur roughly $49M in ARO expenses. This can be fully covered by WLB's Reclamation Deposits, which have a balance of $76.9M, consisting of $43.7M in cash and equivalents and $33.2M in for-sale securities. In essence, the company has already partially funded these liabilities.
Furthermore, of the $404M in ARO, third-parties are responsible for roughly $99M of the reclamation liabilities, thus significantly reducing WLB's long-term ARO liabilities.
Adding those figures together, the total ARO attributable to WLB after deducting for reclamation deposits adds up to $227M, which will be slowly realized over a long period of time. Thus, when we translate the impact to annual cash flow, the amount is relatively small - in 2014, WLB only incurred $7.6M in ARO cash expenses.

3) Post-Retirement Medical Benefits
This liability is an actuarial estimate of the total sum that WLB would have to pay for post-retirement medical benefits for all its retired and current workforce. Again, like many other liabilities on WLB's balance sheet, the impact to cash flow is not as significant as suggested by the size of the liability.

Source: WLB 10-K
Seen above, the estimated cash flow figures are manageable given that WLB continues to churn out stable operating cash flow - on a trailing 12-month basis, WLB had cash from operations of $51.2M, which already includes interest expenses, ARO payables and pension and medical benefits.
Therefore, whilst the size of the liabilities appear large, the impact on WLB's future cash flows are relatively small, assuming operating cash flows do not decline drastically (again, very low probability of this scenario due to long-term cost protected contracts).
Environmental Compliance
A common threat to coal producers is the gradual shift by utilities away from coal-generated power plants due to the high cost of compliance to environmental statutes.
In this aspect, WLB has another advantage over most coal producers: substantially all of its clients are compliant with Mercury and Air Toxics Standards (MATS). That means they are at no imminent threat of being shut down or forced to switch to natural gas and other cleaner fuels.
Moreover, in past conference calls, management has stated explicitly that none of its customers have taken any action or expressed any intention to shut down plants that it is currently supplying due to environmental legislation or otherwise.
Its recent acquisition of Canadian properties has also aided in diversifying this risk, as Canadian laws could be considered more coal-friendly compared to the far more vindictive EPA.

Thus, while the risk from coal-to-gas conversion and plant retirements due to environmental pressures are still present, they are relatively contained in the case of WLB's customers compared to other coal producers.
WMLP Operations
WMLP is a Master Limited Partnership that has a portfolio of coal assets. WLB owns the general partner and has a controlling stake (79%) in WMLP.
WMLP was originally Oxford Resource Partners L.P, but was renamed after being acquired by WLB in a transaction that closed at the end of FY2014. Since then, there has been substantial restructuring of assets and liabilities to maximize the benefit to both WLB and WMLP.
Currently, WMLP operates as a standalone, publicly-traded MLP. However, the strategy that WLB has implemented is one that involves "dropping down" assets to WMLP, which would enable it to increase income and cash flow distributions.
Essentially, management's strategy has been to transfer coal mines and other assets to WMLP in exchange for cash or equity. WMLP would then operate the mines and generate income, thus resulting in higher income for both entities. However, unlike WLB's US and Canadian assets, WMLP's assets are not mine-mouth operations, i.e. the coal has to be transported a far longer distance, which means it does enjoy the same cost and time advantages like WLB's coal mines. As such, it operates in a more competitive market and is vulnerable to more risks.
We view WMLP's operations as a positive as WLB is able to monetize its assets indirectly through this "drop-down" method. It is able to exchange coal assets for either cash or equity in WMLP. This provides short-term liquidity (WLB can sell equity in WMLP if needed) whilst at the same time ensuring higher future income.
Conclusion
Essentially, WLB is a coal miner that operates like a monopoly in its niche markets. Due to permanent advantages like the close proximity of all its mines to the power station and the long-term cost protected contracts that are literally a decade long, it is virtually under no threat from other coal miners or from displacement due to cheap natural gas.

Unlike other coal miners whose sales contracts depend on price adjustments according to the current spot price or other indices, WLB has price and volume visibility for the next 11 years due to the nature of its long-term contracts, thus ensuring it is able to remain profitably in business in tough times.
Moreover, the depressed financial figures for FY2014 due to numerous one-time charges related to acquisition, restructuring and debt extinguishment costs has led investors to overlook the strong fundamentals of the company's business model and its financial sustainability. Certain large liabilities recorded on the balance sheet that have a far smaller impact on cash flow has compounded this problem. Add to that the general pessimism regarding the coal sector and we can safely say that Westmoreland Coal is a diamond in the rough.
Disclosure: I/we have no positions in any stocks mentioned, but may initiate a long position in WLB over the next 72 hours. 
I wrote this article myself, and it expresses my own opinions. I am not receiving compensation for it (other than from Seeking Alpha). I have no business relationship with any company whose stock is mentioned in this article.
